Cross join, and the accidental cartesian product.

A cross join is the explicit cartesian product: every row on the left paired with every row on the right, with no filter. It is occasionally what you want, for example generating a grid of customer and month pairs to left join sales into.

The footgun is the comma-separated from syntax that predates explicit join keywords. From a, b is a cross join. Add a where matching their ids and it becomes an inner join, but forget the where and you silently get n times m rows.

Modern explicit join-on syntax makes this almost impossible. Most engines reject an inner join without an on clause as a syntax error. So always use explicit join syntax in saved code.
